 shortened) form of a Navajo personal name such as <i>Hataałii Yázhí</i>, based on the occupational name <i>hataałii</i> which means literally ‘singer’ and denotes a medicine man. Compare   Hadley   2 and   Singer   6."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Hadley was born about 1100, in Hadley, Shropshire, England. He had at least 2 sons with Seburga or Sibil Peverell. He died in 1136, in his hometown, at the age of 37."},"et":{"about 1100–1136":"umbes 1100–1136","1105–1154":"1105–1154","1130–1194":"1130–1194","–1190":"–1190","1100–1136":"1100–1136","1190":"1190","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1136":"1136","1100":"1100","ABT 1130  (eldest son)":"umbes 1130","1154":"1154","1130":"1130","1194":"1194","about 1100":"umbes 1100","Hadley, Shropshire, England":"Hadley, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1100–1136":"noin 1100–1136","1105–1154":"1105–1154","1130–1194":"1130–1194","–1190":"–1190","1100–1136":"1100–1136","1190":"1